XTT Assay

by Anastasia Abashidze

Blavatnik Center for Drug Discovery

Introduction

XTT Assay

Cell proliferation assays are widely used in cell biology for the study of growth factors, cytokines and media components, and for the screening of cytotoxic agents and for lymphocyte activation. In XTT assay we quantify cell viability using tetrazolium salt XTT. This method is based on the fact that live cells reduce tetrazolium salts into colored formazan compounds. The biochemical procedure is based on the activity of mitochondria enzymes which are inactivated shortly after cell death. XTT is a colorimetric assay, so we measure absorbance.
XTT calculation

{% include image.html style="float: left; margin-right:700px" max-width="350" file="/simplydrug/hts_images/xtt.png" %}

Assay Data

In this experiment we use HEK293 cells to measure toxicity of nine different compounds. Blank wells refer to the absorbance of medium without cells, and each compound has its own blank wells, since some compounds can interfere with absorbance measures. Compound blanks are listed in the 'Status' field in the layout file. CONTROL wells refer to the absorbance of medium with cells, and DMSO is the absorbance of cells with DMSO. We will subtract blanks of compounds from 'raw' absorbance values of compounds and save the result in 'abs_norm' column.

Subtract compound blanks means

{% raw %} 
results = pd.DataFrame()
for name, group in data.groupby('Compound_id'):
    group = group.copy()
    group_blank_mean = data[data.Status == name + '_BL']['raw'].mean()
    print('Compound: ' + name + '     blank mean: ' + str(group_blank_mean))
    group['abs_norm'] = group['raw'] - group_blank_mean
    results = results.append(group, sort = False)
display(results.head(3))

Calculate Survival

{% raw %} 
blank_mean = data[data.Status == 'BL']['raw'].mean()
control_mean = data[data.Status == 'CONTROL']['raw'].mean()

print('Control mean : ', control_mean)
print('Blank mean: ',  blank_mean)

survival = lambda x, y: x*100/y  # survival helper function
results['Response'] = survival(results['abs_norm'], (control_mean - blank_mean))
results = results.dropna().sort_values(by = ['Compound_id', 'Dose'], ascending = False) # IMPORTANT to remove controls!
display(results.head())

Conclusions

Compounds 1, 2, 6, and 7 show nice fitting curves with survival 67-70% and about 90% for compound 7. Compounds 3 and 8 are non-toxic. In contrast, compound 4 is toxic, survival rates are at 0 at all the concentrations. Compounds 5 and 9 show a reduction in survival, but the dose-response fit failed.
